  "prompt": "Does it hurt to get stitches removed?",
  "response": "The process of removing stitches (sutures) typically causes little to no pain for most people. Here\u2019s what to expect:\n\n1. **Sensation**: You may feel a slight tugging or pulling sensation as the stitches are removed, but it\u2019s usually not painful. The area might feel sensitive, especially if the skin is still healing.\n\n2. **Discomfort**: If the wound is still tender or if the stitches have been in for a long time and have started to embed in the skin, you might feel mild discomfort or a quick pinch.\n\n3. **Healing**: By the time stitches are ready to be removed (usually 5\u201314 days, depending on the location and type of wound), the skin has typically healed enough that the process should not be painful.\n\nIf you\u2019re concerned about pain, you can let your healthcare provider know. They can guide you and ensure the process is as comfortable as possible. In some cases, a numbing cream or spray might be used, but this is usually unnecessary.",
